tus>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G021686/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>With publics increasingly disengaging from political parties and institutional politics, we are witnessing the emergence of various political experiments. Some of these take on spectacular qualities and this project examines how such experiments:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>act to interrupt political business-as-usual and demonstrate, and even pre-figure, new and better ways of performing politics; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>hold out the possibility of reconciling and thereby somehow overcoming tensions between representative and more directly democratic modes of political practice; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>offer prospective participants the role of 'active spectator'.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>Using a combination of empirical and more theoretically-informed approaches, the project investigates these experiments contextually as well as more conceptually. It builds on a recently completed PhD project by comparing initiatives taking place across governmental, social movement, popular media and business domains reflecting on a variety of surprising similarities as well crucial differences between these practices. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Results of this project will be communicated via a series of journal publications, a dedicated website, conference papers and via a collaborative interdisciplinary and cross-sectoral workshop geared to producing a 'think-piece'. This will describe and explore these developments in an accessible way and be disseminated to audiences across different sectors.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>68941</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/G021686/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>